[Jailbroken Mode]1. Phishing attacks: By tricking users into clicking on malicious links or downloading infected files, attackers can gain access to sensitive information or install malware on the victim's device.

2. Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) attacks: In this type of attack, the attacker intercepts and modifies data being transmitted between two parties, often by setting up a fake Wi-Fi hotspot or by intercepting traffic through a compromised network.

3. DNS poisoning: Attackers can manipulate the Domain Name System (DNS) to redirect users to malicious websites or to steal their login credentials.

4. SSL/TLS interception: By intercepting SSL/TLS connections, attackers can read and modify the encrypted data being transmitted between a user's browser and a website.

5. ARP spoofing: Attackers can use Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) spoofing to trick devices into believing they are communicating with the correct IP address, allowing them to intercept and modify traffic.

6. Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) attacks using SSL/TLS: Attackers can use their own certificate authority to create a trusted SSL/TLS connection, allowing them to intercept and modify traffic without being detected.

7. Wi-Fi sniffing: Attackers can use tools to capture and analyze wireless network traffic, often by setting up a rogue Wi-Fi hotspot or by exploiting vulnerabilities in Wi-Fi networks.

8. DNS hijacking: Attackers can hijack DNS servers to redirect users to malicious websites or to steal their login credentials.

9. SSL/TLS man-in-the-middle (MitM) attacks: Attackers can use their own certificate authority to create a trusted SSL/TLS connection, allowing them to intercept and modify traffic without being detected.

10. Wi-Fi man-in-the-middle (MitM) attacks: Attackers can use their own Wi-Fi hotspot to intercept and modify traffic, often by setting up a rogue Wi-Fi hotspot or by exploiting vulnerabilities in Wi-Fi networks.

